ce:section.ce:para:
As the most highly negatively charged glycosaminoglycan in biological systems, Hep readily binds to other positively charged substances via electrostatic interactions [20]. Therefore, we tried to use positively charged CDs as probes for Hep. As seen in Fig. 3
                        a, Hep significantly enhanced the fluorescence intensity of CDs. At concentrations of 0.02–16 μM, the fluorescence intensity increased linearly with increasing Hep concentration, and there was a good linear relationship between Hep concentration and fluorescence ratio (F/F0). The corresponding detection limit was calculated to be 0.007 nM this result could be attributed to strong intermolecular interactions, leading to electron transfer and thus enhanced fluorescence [21]. The performance of this probe is good compared to some other optical probes (Table 1
                        ). In particular, the linear range covers the recommended therapeutic range of heparin in cardiovascular surgery (17–67 μM) and in postoperative and long-term care (1.7–10 μM). These two applications require only one probe to perform.
